#: ../../../environments.rst:10
msgid "Environments (spack.yaml, spack.lock)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:12
msgid ""
"An environment is used to group a set of specs intended for some purpose to "
"be built, rebuilt, and deployed in a coherent fashion. Environments define "
"aspects of the installation of the software, such as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:16
msgid "*which* specs to install;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:17
msgid "*how* those specs are configured; and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:18
msgid "*where* the concretized software will be installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:20
msgid ""
"Aggregating this information into an environment for processing has "
"advantages over the *à la carte* approach of building and loading individual "
"Spack modules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:23
msgid ""
"With environments, you concretize, install, or load (activate) all of the "
"specs with a single command. Concretization fully configures the specs and "
"dependencies of the environment in preparation for installing the software. "
"This is a more robust solution than ad-hoc installation scripts. And you can "
"share an environment or even re-use it on a different computer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:29
msgid ""
"Environment definitions, especially *how* specs are configured, allow the "
"software to remain stable and repeatable even when Spack packages are "
"upgraded. Changes are only picked up when the environment is explicitly re-"
"concretized."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:32
msgid ""
"Defining *where* specs are installed supports a filesystem view of the "
"environment. Yet Spack maintains a single installation of the software that "
"can be re-used across multiple environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:36
msgid ""
"Activating an environment determines *when* all of the associated (and "
"installed) specs are loaded so limits the software loaded to those specs "
"actually needed by the environment. Spack can even generate a script to load "
"all modules related to an environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:41
msgid ""
"Other packaging systems also provide environments that are similar in some "
"ways to Spack environments; for example, `Conda environments <https://conda."
"io/docs/user-guide/tasks/manage-environments.html>`_ or `Python Virtual "
"Environments <https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/venv.html>`_.  Spack "
"environments provide some distinctive features though:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:48
msgid ""
"A spec installed \"in\" an environment is no different from the same spec "
"installed anywhere else in Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:50
msgid "Spack environments may contain more than one spec of the same package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:53
msgid ""
"Spack uses a \"manifest and lock\" model similar to `Bundler gemfiles "
"<https://bundler.io/man/gemfile.5.html>`_ and other package managers. The "
"environment's user input file (or manifest), is named ``spack.yaml``. The "
"lock file, which contains the fully configured and concretized specs, is "
"named ``spack.lock``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:63
msgid "Using Environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:65
msgid ""
"Here we follow a typical use case of creating, concretizing, installing and "
"loading an environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:70
msgid "Creating a managed Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:72
msgid "An environment is created by:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:74
msgid "$ spack env create myenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:78
msgid ""
"The directory ``$SPACK_ROOT/var/spack/environments/myenv`` is created to "
"manage the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:83
msgid ""
"All managed environments by default are stored in the ``$SPACK_ROOT/var/"
"spack/environments`` folder. This location can be changed by setting the "
"``environments_root`` variable in ``config.yaml``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:87
msgid ""
"Spack creates the file ``spack.yaml``, hidden directory ``.spack-env``, and "
"``spack.lock`` file under ``$SPACK_ROOT/var/spack/environments/myenv``. User "
"interaction occurs through the ``spack.yaml`` file and the Spack commands "
"that affect it. Metadata and, by default, the view are stored in the ``."
"spack-env`` directory. When the environment is concretized, Spack creates "
"the ``spack.lock`` file with the fully configured specs and dependencies for "
"the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:95
msgid "The ``.spack-env`` subdirectory also contains:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:97
msgid ""
"``repo/``: A subdirectory acting as the repo consisting of the Spack "
"packages used in the environment. It allows the environment to build the "
"same, in theory, even on different versions of Spack with different packages!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:101
msgid ""
"``logs/``: A subdirectory containing the build logs for the packages in this "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:104
msgid ""
"Spack Environments can also be created from either the user input, or "
"manifest, file or the lockfile. Create an environment from a manifest using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:107
msgid "$ spack env create myenv spack.yaml"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:111
msgid ""
"The resulting environment is guaranteed to have the same root specs as the "
"original but may concretize differently in the presence of different "
"explicit or default configuration settings (e.g., a different version of "
"Spack or for a different user account)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:116
msgid "Create an environment from a ``spack.lock`` file using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:118
msgid "$ spack env create myenv spack.lock"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:122
msgid ""
"The resulting environment, when on the same or a compatible machine, is "
"guaranteed to initially have the same concrete specs as the original."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:127
msgid "Environment creation also accepts a full path to the file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:129
msgid ""
"If the path is not under the ``$SPACK_ROOT/var/spack/environments`` "
"directory then the source is referred to as an :ref:`independent environment "
"<independent_environments>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:135
msgid "Activating an Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:137
msgid "To activate an environment, use the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:139
msgid "$ spack env activate myenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:143
msgid ""
"By default, the ``spack env activate`` will load the view associated with "
"the environment into the user environment. The ``-v, --with-view`` argument "
"ensures this behavior, and the ``-V, --without-view`` argument activates the "
"environment without changing the user environment variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:149
msgid ""
"The ``-p`` option to the ``spack env activate`` command modifies the user's "
"prompt to begin with the environment name in brackets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:152
msgid ""
"$ spack env activate -p myenv\n"
"[myenv] $ ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:157
msgid ""
"The ``activate`` command can also be used to create a new environment, if it "
"is not already defined, by adding the ``--create`` flag. Managed and "
"independent environments can both be created using the same flags that "
"`spack env create` accepts.  If an environment already exists then spack "
"will simply activate it and ignore the create-specific flags."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:163
msgid ""
"$ spack env activate --create -p myenv\n"
"# ...\n"
"# [creates if myenv does not exist yet]\n"
"# ...\n"
"[myenv] $ ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:171
msgid "To deactivate an environment, use the command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:173
msgid "$ spack env deactivate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:177
msgid "or the shortcut alias"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:179
msgid "$ despacktivate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:183
msgid ""
"If the environment was activated with its view, deactivating the environment "
"will remove the view from the user environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:190
msgid "Independent Environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:192
msgid ""
"Independent environments can be located in any directory outside of Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:196
msgid ""
"When uninstalling packages, Spack asks the user to confirm the removal of "
"packages that are still used in a managed environment. This is not the case "
"for independent environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:200
msgid ""
"To create an independent environment, use one of the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:202
msgid ""
"$ spack env create --dir my_env\n"
"$ spack env create ./my_env"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:207
msgid ""
"As a shorthand, you can also create an independent environment upon "
"activation if it does not already exist:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:210
msgid "$ spack env activate --create ./my_env"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:214
msgid ""
"For convenience, Spack can also place an independent environment in a "
"temporary directory for you:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:216
msgid "$ spack env activate --temp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:223
msgid "Environment-Aware Commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:225
msgid ""
"Spack commands are environment-aware. For example, the ``find`` command "
"shows only the specs in the active environment if an environment has been "
"activated. Otherwise it shows all specs in the Spack instance. The same rule "
"applies to the ``install`` and ``uninstall`` commands."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:231
msgid ""
"$ spack find\n"
"==> 0 installed packages\n"
"\n"
"$ spack install zlib@1.2.11\n"
"==> Installing zlib-1.2.11-q6cqrdto4iktfg6qyqcc5u4vmfmwb7iv\n"
"==> No binary for zlib-1.2.11-q6cqrdto4iktfg6qyqcc5u4vmfmwb7iv found: "
"installing from source\n"
"==> zlib: Executing phase: 'install'\n"
"[+] ~/spack/opt/spack/linux-rhel7-broadwell/gcc-8.1.0/zlib-1.2.11-"
"q6cqrdto4iktfg6qyqcc5u4vmfmwb7iv\n"
"\n"
"$ spack env activate myenv\n"
"\n"
"$ spack find\n"
"==> In environment myenv\n"
"==> No root specs\n"
"==> 0 installed packages\n"
"\n"
"$ spack install zlib@1.2.8\n"
"==> Installing zlib-1.2.8-yfc7epf57nsfn2gn4notccaiyxha6z7x\n"
"==> No binary for zlib-1.2.8-yfc7epf57nsfn2gn4notccaiyxha6z7x found: "
"installing from source\n"
"==> zlib: Executing phase: 'install'\n"
"[+] ~/spack/opt/spack/linux-rhel7-broadwell/gcc-8.1.0/zlib-1.2.8-"
"yfc7epf57nsfn2gn4notccaiyxha6z7x\n"
"==> Updating view at ~/spack/var/spack/environments/myenv/.spack-env/view\n"
"\n"
"$ spack find\n"
"==> In environment myenv\n"
"==> Root specs\n"
"zlib@1.2.8\n"
"\n"
"==> 1 installed package\n"
"-- linux-rhel7-broadwell / gcc@8.1.0 ----------------------------\n"
"zlib@1.2.8\n"
"\n"
"$ despacktivate\n"
"\n"
"$ spack find\n"
"==> 2 installed packages\n"
"-- linux-rhel7-broadwell / gcc@8.1.0 ----------------------------\n"
"zlib@1.2.8  zlib@1.2.11"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:273
msgid ""
"Note that when we installed the abstract spec ``zlib@1.2.8``, it was "
"presented as a root of the environment. All explicitly installed packages "
"will be listed as roots of the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:277
msgid ""
"All of the Spack commands that act on the list of installed specs are "
"environment-aware in this way, including ``install``, ``uninstall``, "
"``find``, ``extensions``, etcetera. In the :ref:`environment-configuration` "
"section we will discuss environment-aware commands further."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:285
msgid "Adding Abstract Specs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:287
msgid ""
"An abstract spec is the user-specified spec before Spack applies defaults or "
"dependency information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:290
msgid ""
"Users can add abstract specs to an environment using the ``spack add`` "
"command. The most important component of an environment is a list of "
"abstract specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:294
msgid ""
"Adding a spec adds it as a root spec of the environment in the user input "
"file (``spack.yaml``). It does not affect the concrete specs in the lock "
"file (``spack.lock``) and it does not install the spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:298
msgid ""
"The ``spack add`` command is environment-aware. It adds the spec to the "
"currently active environment. An error is generated if there isn't an active "
"environment. All environment-aware commands can also be called using the "
"``spack -e`` flag to specify the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:303
msgid ""
"$ spack env activate myenv\n"
"$ spack add mpileaks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:308
msgid "or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:310
msgid "$ spack -e myenv add python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:318
msgid "Concretizing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:320
msgid ""
"Once user specs have been added to an environment, they can be concretized. "
"There are three different modes of operation to concretize an environment, "
"explained in detail in :ref:`environments_concretization_config`. Regardless "
"of which mode of operation is chosen, the following command will ensure all "
"of the root specs are concretized according to the constraints that are "
"prescribed in the configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:327
msgid "[myenv]$ spack concretize"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:331
msgid ""
"In the case of specs that are not concretized together, the command above "
"will concretize only the specs that were added and not yet concretized. "
"Forcing a re-concretization of all of the specs can be done by adding the ``-"
"f`` option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:336
msgid "[myenv]$ spack concretize -f"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:340
msgid ""
"Without the option, Spack guarantees that already concretized specs are "
"unchanged in the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:343
msgid ""
"The ``concretize`` command does not install any packages. For packages that "
"have already been installed outside of the environment, the process of "
"adding the spec and concretizing is identical to installing the spec "
"assuming it concretizes to the exact spec that was installed outside of the "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:349
msgid ""
"The ``spack find`` command can show concretized specs separately from "
"installed specs using the ``-c`` (``--concretized``) flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:352
msgid ""
"[myenv]$ spack add zlib\n"
"[myenv]$ spack concretize\n"
"[myenv]$ spack find -c\n"
"==> In environment myenv\n"
"==> Root specs\n"
"zlib\n"
"\n"
"==> Concretized roots\n"
"-- linux-rhel7-x86_64 / gcc@4.9.3 -------------------------------\n"
"zlib@1.2.11\n"
"\n"
"==> 0 installed packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:372
msgid "Installing an Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:374
msgid ""
"In addition to adding individual specs to an environment, one can install "
"the entire environment at once using the command"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:377
msgid "[myenv]$ spack install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:381
msgid ""
"If the environment has been concretized, Spack will install the concretized "
"specs. Otherwise, ``spack install`` will concretize the environment before "
"installing the concretized specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:387
msgid ""
"Every ``spack install`` process builds one package at a time with multiple "
"build jobs, controlled by the ``-j`` flag and the ``config:build_jobs`` "
"option (see :ref:`build-jobs`). To speed up environment builds further, "
"independent packages can be installed in parallel by launching more Spack "
"instances. For example, the following will build at most four packages in "
"parallel using three background jobs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:394
msgid "[myenv]$ spack install & spack install & spack install & spack install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:398
msgid ""
"Another option is to generate a ``Makefile`` and run ``make -j<N>`` to "
"control the number of parallel install processes. See :ref:`env-generate-"
"depfile` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:403
msgid ""
"As it installs, ``spack install`` creates symbolic links in the ``logs/`` "
"directory in the environment, allowing for easy inspection of build logs "
"related to that environment. The ``spack install`` command also stores a "
"Spack repo containing the ``package.py`` file used at install time for each "
"package in the ``repos/`` directory in the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:410
msgid ""
"The ``--no-add`` option can be used in a concrete environment to tell spack "
"to install specs already present in the environment but not to add any new "
"root specs to the environment.  For root specs provided to ``spack install`` "
"on the command line, ``--no-add`` is the default, while for dependency "
"specs, it is optional.  In other words, if there is an unambiguous match in "
"the active concrete environment for a root spec provided to ``spack "
"install`` on the command line, spack does not require you to specify the ``--"
"no-add`` option to prevent the spec from being added again.  At the same "
"time, a spec that already exists in the environment, but only as a "
"dependency, will be added to the environment as a root spec without the ``--"
"no-add`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:424
msgid "Developing Packages in a Spack Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:426
msgid ""
"The ``spack develop`` command allows one to develop Spack packages in an "
"environment. It requires a spec containing a concrete version, and will "
"configure Spack to install the package from local source.  If a version is "
"not provided from the command line interface then spack  will automatically "
"pick the highest version the package has defined. This means any infinity "
"versions (``develop``, ``main``, ``stable``) will be preferred in this "
"selection process. By default, ``spack develop`` will also clone the package "
"to a subdirectory in the environment for the local source. This package will "
"have a special variant ``dev_path`` set, and Spack will ensure the package "
"and its dependents are rebuilt any time the environment is installed if the "
"package's local source code has been modified. Spack's native implementation "
"to check for modifications is to check if ``mtime`` is newer than the "
"installation. A custom check can be created by overriding the "
"``detect_dev_src_change`` method  in your package class. This is "
"particularly useful for projects using custom spack repo's  to drive "
"development and want to optimize performance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:443
msgid ""
"Spack ensures that all instances of a developed package in the environment "
"are concretized to match the version (and other constraints) passed as the "
"spec argument to the ``spack develop`` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:448
msgid ""
"For packages with ``git`` attributes, git branches, tags, and commits can "
"also be used as valid concrete versions (see :ref:`version-specifier`). This "
"means that for a package ``foo``, ``spack develop foo@git.main`` will clone "
"the ``main`` branch of the package, and ``spack install`` will install from "
"that git clone if ``foo`` is in the environment. Further development on "
"``foo`` can be tested by re-installing the environment, and eventually "
"committed and pushed to the upstream git repo."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:456
msgid ""
"If the package being developed supports out-of-source builds then users can "
"use the ``--build_directory`` flag to control the location and name of the "
"build directory.  This is a shortcut to set the ``package_attributes:"
"build_directory`` in the ``packages`` configuration (see :ref:`assigning-"
"package-attributes`). The supplied location will become the build-directory "
"for that package in all future builds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:463
msgid "Potential pitfalls of setting the build directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:464
msgid ""
"Spack does not check for out-of-source build compatibility with the packages "
"and so the onerous of making sure the package supports out-of-source builds "
"is on the user. For example, most ``autotool`` and ``makefile`` packages do "
"not support out-of-source builds while all ``CMake`` packages do. "
"Understanding these nuances are on the software developers and we strongly "
"encourage developers to only redirect the build directory if they understand "
"their package's build-system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:475
msgid "Loading"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:477
msgid ""
"Once an environment has been installed, the following creates a load script "
"for it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:480
msgid "$ spack env loads -r"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:484
msgid ""
"This creates a file called ``loads`` in the environment directory. Sourcing "
"that file in Bash will make the environment available to the user; and can "
"be included in ``.bashrc`` files, etc.  The ``loads`` file may also be "
"copied out of the environment, renamed, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:494
msgid "Included Concrete Environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:496
msgid ""
"Spack environments can create an environment based off of information in "
"already established environments. You can think of it as a combination of "
"existing environments. It will gather information from the existing "
"environment's ``spack.lock`` and use that during the creation of this "
"included concrete environment. When an included concrete environment is "
"created it will generate a ``spack.lock`` file for the newly created "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:506
msgid "Creating included environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:507
msgid ""
"To create a combined concrete environment, you must have at least one "
"existing concrete environment. You will use the command ``spack env create`` "
"with the argument ``--include-concrete`` followed by the name or path of the "
"environment you'd like to include. Here is an example of how to create a "
"combined environment from the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:513
msgid ""
"$ spack env create myenv\n"
"$ spack -e myenv add python\n"
"$ spack -e myenv concretize\n"
"$ spack env create --include-concrete myenv included_env"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:521
msgid ""
"You can also include an environment directly in the ``spack.yaml`` file. It "
"involves adding the ``include_concrete`` heading in the yaml followed by the "
"absolute path to the independent environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:525
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs: []\n"
"  concretizer:\n"
"      unify: true\n"
"  include_concrete:\n"
"  - /absolute/path/to/environment1\n"
"  - /absolute/path/to/environment2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:536
msgid ""
"Once the ``spack.yaml`` has been updated you must concretize the environment "
"to get the concrete specs from the included environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:541
msgid "Updating an included environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:542
msgid ""
"If changes were made to the base environment and you want that reflected in "
"the included environment you will need to reconcretize both the base "
"environment and the included environment for the change to be implemented. "
"For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:546
msgid ""
"$ spack env create myenv\n"
"$ spack -e myenv add python\n"
"$ spack -e myenv concretize\n"
"$ spack env create --include-concrete myenv included_env\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"$ spack -e myenv find\n"
"==> In environment myenv\n"
"==> Root specs\n"
"python\n"
"\n"
"==> 0 installed packages\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"$ spack -e included_env find\n"
"==> In environment included_env\n"
"==> No root specs\n"
"==> Included specs\n"
"python\n"
"\n"
"==> 0 installed packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:570
msgid ""
"Here we see that ``included_env`` has access to the python package through "
"the ``myenv`` environment. But if we were to add another spec to ``myenv``, "
"``included_env`` will not be able to access the new information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:574
msgid ""
"$ spack -e myenv add perl\n"
"$ spack -e myenv concretize\n"
"$ spack -e myenv find\n"
"==> In environment myenv\n"
"==> Root specs\n"
"perl  python\n"
"\n"
"==> 0 installed packages\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"$ spack -e included_env find\n"
"==> In environment included_env\n"
"==> No root specs\n"
"==> Included specs\n"
"python\n"
"\n"
"==> 0 installed packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:594
msgid ""
"It isn't until you run the ``spack concretize`` command that the combined "
"environment will get the updated information from the reconcretized base "
"environmennt."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:597
msgid ""
"$ spack -e included_env concretize\n"
"$ spack -e included_env find\n"
"==> In environment included_env\n"
"==> No root specs\n"
"==> Included specs\n"
"perl  python\n"
"\n"
"==> 0 installed packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:612
msgid "Configuring Environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:614
msgid ""
"A variety of Spack behaviors are changed through Spack configuration files, "
"covered in more detail in the :ref:`configuration` section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:618
msgid ""
"Spack Environments provide an additional level of configuration scope "
"between the custom scope and the user scope discussed in the configuration "
"documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:622
msgid ""
"There are two ways to include configuration information in a Spack "
"Environment:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:624
msgid "Inline in the ``spack.yaml`` file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:626
msgid "Included in the ``spack.yaml`` file from another file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:628
msgid ""
"Many Spack commands also affect configuration information in files "
"automatically. Those commands take a ``--scope`` argument, and the "
"environment can be specified by ``env:NAME`` (to affect environment ``foo``, "
"set ``--scope env:foo``). These commands will automatically manipulate "
"configuration inline in the ``spack.yaml`` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:636
msgid "Inline configurations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:638
msgid ""
"Inline environment-scope configuration is done using the same yaml format as "
"standard Spack configuration scopes, covered in the :ref:`configuration` "
"section. Each section is contained under a top-level yaml object with it's "
"name. For example, a ``spack.yaml`` manifest file containing some package "
"preference configuration (as in a ``packages.yaml`` file) could contain:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:645
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  # ...\n"
"  packages:\n"
"    all:\n"
"      compiler: [intel]\n"
"  # ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:654
msgid ""
"This configuration sets the default compiler for all packages to ``intel``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:659
msgid "Included configurations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:661
msgid ""
"Spack environments allow an ``include`` heading in their yaml schema. This "
"heading pulls in external configuration files and applies them to the "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:665
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  include:\n"
"  - relative/path/to/config.yaml\n"
"  - https://github.com/path/to/raw/config/compilers.yaml\n"
"  - /absolute/path/to/packages.yaml"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:673
msgid ""
"Environments can include files or URLs. File paths can be relative or "
"absolute. URLs include the path to the text for individual files or can be "
"the path to a directory containing configuration files. Spack supports "
"``file``, ``http``, ``https`` and ``ftp`` protocols (or schemes). Spack-"
"specific, environment and user path variables may be used in these paths. "
"See :ref:`config-file-variables` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:682
msgid "Configuration precedence"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:684
msgid ""
"Inline configurations take precedence over included configurations, so you "
"don't have to change shared configuration files to make small changes to an "
"individual environment. Included configurations listed earlier will have "
"higher precedence, as the included configs are applied in reverse order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:691
msgid "Manually Editing the Specs List"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:693
msgid ""
"The list of abstract/root specs in the environment is maintained in the "
"``spack.yaml`` manifest under the heading ``specs``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:696
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"    specs:\n"
"      - ncview\n"
"      - netcdf\n"
"      - nco\n"
"      - py-sphinx"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:705
msgid ""
"Appending to this list in the yaml is identical to using the ``spack add`` "
"command from the command line. However, there is more power available from "
"the yaml file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:713
msgid "Spec concretization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:714
msgid ""
"An environment can be concretized in three different modes and the behavior "
"active under any environment is determined by the ``concretizer:unify`` "
"configuration option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:717
msgid "The *default* mode is to unify all specs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:719
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"    specs:\n"
"      - hdf5+mpi\n"
"      - zlib@1.2.8\n"
"    concretizer:\n"
"      unify: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:728
msgid ""
"This means that any package in the environment corresponds to a single "
"concrete spec. In the above example, when ``hdf5`` depends down the line of "
"``zlib``, it is required to take ``zlib@1.2.8`` instead of a newer version. "
"This mode of concretization is particularly useful when environment views "
"are used: if every package occurs in only one flavor, it is usually possible "
"to merge all install directories into a view."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:734
msgid ""
"A downside of unified concretization is that it can be overly strict. For "
"example, a concretization error would happen when both ``hdf5+mpi`` and "
"``hdf5~mpi`` are specified in an environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:738
msgid ""
"The second mode is to *unify when possible*: this makes concretization of "
"root specs more independendent. Instead of requiring reuse of dependencies "
"across different root specs, it is only maximized:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:742
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"    specs:\n"
"      - hdf5~mpi\n"
"      - hdf5+mpi\n"
"      - zlib@1.2.8\n"
"    concretizer:\n"
"      unify: when_possible"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:752
msgid ""
"This means that both ``hdf5`` installations will use ``zlib@1.2.8`` as a "
"dependency even if newer versions of that library are available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:755
msgid ""
"The third mode of operation is to concretize root specs entirely "
"independently by disabling unified concretization:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:758
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"    specs:\n"
"      - hdf5~mpi\n"
"      - hdf5+mpi\n"
"      - zlib@1.2.8\n"
"    concretizer:\n"
"      unify: false"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:768
msgid ""
"In this example ``hdf5`` is concretized separately, and does not consider "
"``zlib@1.2.8`` as a constraint or preference. Instead, it will take the "
"latest possible version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:771
msgid ""
"The last two concretization options are typically useful for system "
"administrators and user support groups providing a large software stack for "
"their HPC center."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:776
msgid ""
"The ``concretizer:unify`` config option was introduced in Spack 0.18 to "
"replace the ``concretization`` property. For reference, ``concretization: "
"together`` is replaced by ``concretizer:unify:true``, and ``concretization: "
"separately`` is replaced by ``concretizer:unify:false``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:781
msgid "Re-concretization of user specs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:783
msgid ""
"The ``spack concretize`` command without additional arguments will *not* "
"change any previously concretized specs. This may prevent it from finding a "
"solution when using ``unify: true``, and it may prevent it from finding a "
"minimal solution when using ``unify: when_possible``. You can force Spack to "
"ignore the existing concrete environment with ``spack concretize -f``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:791
msgid "Spec Matrices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:793
msgid ""
"Entries in the ``specs`` list can be individual abstract specs or a spec "
"matrix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:796
msgid ""
"A spec matrix is a yaml object containing multiple lists of specs, and "
"evaluates to the cross-product of those specs. Spec matrices also contain an "
"``excludes`` directive, which eliminates certain combinations from the "
"evaluated result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:801
msgid "The following two environment manifests are identical:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:803
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"    - zlib %gcc@7.1.0\n"
"    - zlib %gcc@4.9.3\n"
"    - libelf %gcc@7.1.0\n"
"    - libelf %gcc@4.9.3\n"
"    - libdwarf %gcc@7.1.0\n"
"    - cmake\n"
"\n"
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"    - matrix:\n"
"        - [zlib, libelf, libdwarf]\n"
"        - ['%gcc@7.1.0', '%gcc@4.9.3']\n"
"      exclude:\n"
"        - libdwarf%gcc@4.9.3\n"
"    - cmake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:823
msgid ""
"Spec matrices can be used to install swaths of software across various "
"toolchains."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:828
msgid "Spec List References"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:830
msgid "The last type of possible entry in the specs list is a reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:832
msgid ""
"The Spack Environment manifest yaml schema contains an additional heading "
"``definitions``. Under definitions is an array of yaml objects. Each object "
"has one or two fields. The one required field is a name, and the optional "
"field is a ``when`` clause."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:837
msgid ""
"The named field is a spec list. The spec list uses the same syntax as the "
"``specs`` entry. Each entry in the spec list can be a spec, a spec matrix, "
"or a reference to an earlier named list. References are specified using the "
"``$`` sigil, and are \"splatted\" into place (i.e. the elements of the "
"referent are at the same level as the elements listed separately). As an "
"example, the following two manifest files are identical."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:845
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  definitions:\n"
"    - first: [libelf, libdwarf]\n"
"    - compilers: ['%gcc', '%intel']\n"
"    - second:\n"
"        - $first\n"
"        - matrix:\n"
"            - [zlib]\n"
"            - [$compilers]\n"
"  specs:\n"
"    - $second\n"
"    - cmake\n"
"\n"
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"    - libelf\n"
"    - libdwarf\n"
"    - zlib%gcc\n"
"    - zlib%intel\n"
"    - cmake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:870
msgid ""
"Named spec lists in the definitions section may only refer to a named list "
"defined above itself. Order matters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:873
msgid ""
"In short files like the example, it may be easier to simply list the "
"included specs. However for more complicated examples involving many "
"packages across many toolchains, separately factored lists make environments "
"substantially more manageable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:878
msgid ""
"Additionally, the ``-l`` option to the ``spack add`` command allows one to "
"add to named lists in the definitions section of the manifest file directly "
"from the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:882
msgid ""
"The ``when`` directive can be used to conditionally add specs to a named "
"list. The ``when`` directive takes a string of Python code referring to a "
"restricted set of variables, and evaluates to a boolean. The specs listed "
"are appended to the named list if the ``when`` string evaluates to ``True``. "
"In the following snippet, the named list ``compilers`` is ``['%gcc', "
"'%clang', '%intel']`` on ``x86_64`` systems and ``['%gcc', '%clang']`` on "
"all other systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:890
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  definitions:\n"
"    - compilers: ['%gcc', '%clang']\n"
"    - when: arch.satisfies('target=x86_64:')\n"
"      compilers: ['%intel']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:900
msgid ""
"Any definitions with the same named list with true ``when`` clauses (or "
"absent ``when`` clauses) will be appended together"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:903
msgid "The valid variables for a ``when`` clause are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:905
msgid ""
"``platform``. The platform string of the default Spack architecture on the "
"system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:908
msgid "``os``. The os string of the default Spack architecture on the system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:911
msgid ""
"``target``. The target string of the default Spack architecture on the "
"system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:914
msgid ""
"``architecture`` or ``arch``. A Spack spec satisfying the default Spack "
"architecture on the system. This supports querying via the ``satisfies`` "
"method, as shown above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:918
msgid ""
"``arch_str``. The architecture string of the default Spack architecture on "
"the system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:921
msgid "``re``. The standard regex module in Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:923
msgid "``env``. The user environment (usually ``os.environ`` in Python)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:925
msgid ""
"``hostname``. The hostname of the system (if ``hostname`` is an executable "
"in the user's PATH)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:930
msgid "SpecLists as Constraints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:932
msgid ""
"Dependencies and compilers in Spack can be both packages in an environment "
"and constraints on other packages. References to SpecLists allow a shorthand "
"to treat packages in a list as either a compiler or a dependency using the "
"``$%`` or ``$^`` syntax respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:937
msgid ""
"For example, the following environment has three root packages: "
"``gcc@8.1.0``, ``mvapich2@2.3.1 %gcc@8.1.0``, and ``hdf5+mpi %gcc@8.1.0 "
"^mvapich2@2.3.1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:941
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  definitions:\n"
"  - compilers: [gcc@8.1.0]\n"
"  - mpis: [mvapich2@2.3.1]\n"
"  - packages: [hdf5+mpi]\n"
"\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - $compilers\n"
"  - matrix:\n"
"    - [$mpis]\n"
"    - [$%compilers]\n"
"  - matrix:\n"
"    - [$packages]\n"
"    - [$^mpis]\n"
"    - [$%compilers]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:959
msgid ""
"This allows for a much-needed reduction in redundancy between packages and "
"constraints."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:965
msgid "Environment Views"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:967
msgid ""
"Spack Environments can have an associated filesystem view, which is a "
"directory with a more traditional structure ``<view>/bin``, ``<view>/lib``, "
"``<view>/include`` in which all files of the installed packages are linked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:971
msgid ""
"By default a view is created for each environment, thanks to the ``view: "
"true`` option in the ``spack.yaml`` manifest file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:974
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs: [perl, python]\n"
"  view: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:980
msgid ""
"The view is created in a hidden directory ``.spack-env/view`` relative to "
"the environment. If you've used ``spack env activate``, you may have already "
"interacted with this view. Spack prepends its ``<view>/bin`` dir to ``PATH`` "
"when the environment is activated, so that you can directly run executables "
"from all installed packages in the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:985
msgid ""
"Views are highly customizable: you can control where they are put, modify "
"their structure, include and exclude specs, change how files are linked, and "
"you can even generate multiple views for a single environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:993
msgid "Minimal view configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:995
msgid "The minimal configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:997
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  # ...\n"
"  view: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1003
msgid ""
"lets Spack generate a single view with default settings under the ``.spack-"
"env/view`` directory of the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1006
msgid ""
"Another short way to configure a view is to specify just where to put it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1008
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  # ...\n"
"  view: /path/to/view"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1014
msgid "Views can also be disabled by setting ``view: false``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1018
msgid "Advanced view configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1020
msgid ""
"One or more **view descriptors** can be defined under ``view``, keyed by a "
"name. The example from the previous section with ``view: /path/to/view`` is "
"equivalent to defining a view descriptor named ``default`` with a ``root`` "
"attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1024
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  # ...\n"
"  view:\n"
"    default:  # name of the view\n"
"      root: /path/to/view  # view descriptor attribute"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1032
msgid ""
"The ``default`` view descriptor name is special: when you ``spack env "
"activate`` your environment, this view will be used to update (among other "
"things) your ``PATH`` variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1036
msgid ""
"View descriptors must contain the root of the view, and optionally "
"projections, ``select`` and ``exclude`` lists and link information via "
"``link`` and ``link_type``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1040
msgid ""
"As a more advanced example, in the following manifest file snippet we define "
"a view named ``mpis``, rooted at ``/path/to/view`` in which all projections "
"use the package name, version, and compiler name to determine the path for a "
"given package. This view selects all packages that depend on MPI, and "
"excludes those built with the PGI compiler at version 18.5. The root specs "
"with their (transitive) link and run type dependencies will be put in the "
"view due to the  ``link: all`` option, and the files in the view will be "
"symlinks to the spack install directories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1051
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  # ...\n"
"  view:\n"
"    mpis:\n"
"      root: /path/to/view\n"
"      select: [^mpi]\n"
"      exclude: ['%pgi@18.5']\n"
"      projections:\n"
"        all: '{name}/{version}-{compiler.name}'\n"
"      link: all\n"
"      link_type: symlink"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1065
msgid ""
"The default for the ``select`` and ``exclude`` values is to select "
"everything and exclude nothing. The default projection is the default view "
"projection (``{}``). The ``link`` attribute allows the following values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1070
msgid ""
"``link: all`` include root specs with their transitive run and link type "
"dependencies (default);"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1072
msgid ""
"``link: run`` include root specs with their transitive run type dependencies;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1073
msgid "``link: roots`` include root specs without their dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1075
msgid ""
"The ``link_type`` defaults to ``symlink`` but can also take the value of "
"``hardlink`` or ``copy``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1080
msgid ""
"The option ``link: run`` can be used to create small environment views for "
"Python packages. Python will be able to import packages *inside* of the view "
"even when the environment is not activated, and linked libraries will be "
"located *outside* of the view thanks to rpaths."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1085
msgid ""
"From the command line, the ``spack env create`` command takes an argument "
"``--with-view [PATH]`` that sets the path for a single, default view. If no "
"path is specified, the default path is used (``view: true``). The argument "
"``--without-view`` can be used to create an environment without any view "
"configured."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1091
msgid ""
"The ``spack env view`` command can be used to change the manage views of an "
"environment. The subcommand ``spack env view enable`` will add a view named "
"``default`` to an environment. It takes an optional argument to specify the "
"path for the new default view. The subcommand ``spack env view disable`` "
"will remove the view named ``default`` from an environment if one exists. "
"The subcommand ``spack env view regenerate`` will regenerate the views for "
"the environment. This will apply any updates in the environment "
"configuration that have not yet been applied."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1105
msgid "View Projections"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1106
msgid ""
"The default projection into a view is to link every package into the root of "
"the view. The projections attribute is a mapping of partial specs to spec "
"format strings, defined by the :meth:`~spack.spec.Spec.format` function, as "
"shown in the example below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1111
msgid ""
"projections:\n"
"  zlib: \"{name}-{version}\"\n"
"  ^mpi: \"{name}-{version}/{^mpi.name}-{^mpi.version}-{compiler.name}-"
"{compiler.version}\"\n"
"  all: \"{name}-{version}/{compiler.name}-{compiler.version}\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1118
msgid ""
"Projections also permit environment and spack configuration variable "
"expansions as shown below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1121
msgid ""
"projections:\n"
"  all: \"{name}-{version}/{compiler.name}-{compiler.version}/$date/"
"$SYSTEM_ENV_VARIBLE\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1126
msgid ""
"where ``$date`` is the spack configuration variable that will expand with "
"the ``YYYY-MM-DD`` format and ``$SYSTEM_ENV_VARIABLE`` is an environment "
"variable defined in the shell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1129
msgid ""
"The entries in the projections configuration file must all be either specs "
"or the keyword ``all``. For each spec, the projection used will be the first "
"non-``all`` entry that the spec satisfies, or ``all`` if there is an entry "
"for ``all`` and no other entry is satisfied by the spec. Where the keyword "
"``all`` appears in the file does not matter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1136
msgid ""
"Given the example above, the spec ``zlib@1.2.8`` will be linked into ``/my/"
"view/zlib-1.2.8/``, the spec ``hdf5@1.8.10+mpi %gcc@4.9.3 ^mvapich2@2.2`` "
"will be linked into ``/my/view/hdf5-1.8.10/mvapich2-2.2-gcc-4.9.3``, and the "
"spec ``hdf5@1.8.10~mpi %gcc@4.9.3`` will be linked into ``/my/view/"
"hdf5-1.8.10/gcc-4.9.3``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1143
msgid ""
"If the keyword ``all`` does not appear in the projections configuration "
"file, any spec that does not satisfy any entry in the file will be linked "
"into the root of the view as in a single-prefix view. Any entries that "
"appear below the keyword ``all`` in the projections configuration file will "
"not be used, as all specs will use the projection under ``all`` before "
"reaching those entries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1152
msgid "Activating environment views"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1154
msgid "The ``spack env activate <env>`` has two effects:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1156
msgid ""
"It activates the environment so that further Spack commands such as ``spack "
"install`` will run in the context of the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1158
msgid ""
"It activates the view so that environment variables such as ``PATH`` are "
"updated to include the view."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1161
msgid ""
"Without further arguments, the ``default`` view of the environment is "
"activated. If a view with a different name has to be activated, ``spack env "
"activate --with-view <name> <env>`` can be used instead. You can also "
"activate the environment without modifying further environment variables "
"using ``--without-view``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1167
msgid ""
"The environment variables affected by the ``spack env activate`` command and "
"the paths that are used to update them are determined by the :ref:`prefix "
"inspections <customize-env-modifications>` defined in your modules "
"configuration; the defaults are summarized in the following table."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1174
msgid "Variable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1174
msgid "Paths"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1176
msgid "PATH"
msgstr ""

